Description: An apple is a round, edible fruit produced by an apple tree.
The potato is a starchy root vegetable native to the Americas that is consumed as a staple food in many parts of the world.
Bananas are elongated, edible fruits produced by various species of large herbaceous flowering plants in the genus Musa.
Carrots are root vegetables, typically orange in color, that are crisp and sweet.
Chicken breast is a lean cut of meat from the chest of a chicken, known for being a good source of protein.
Broccoli is an edible green plant in the cabbage family, whose large flowering head and stalk are eaten as a vegetable.
Salmon is a fatty fish rich in omega-3 fatty acids, commonly consumed grilled, baked, or smoked.
Oranges are citrus fruits known for their juicy, sweet-tart flavor and high vitamin C content.
Rice is a staple food in many cultures, consisting of small grains that are cooked and eaten as a side or main dish.
Eggs are laid by birds, especially chickens, and are commonly consumed for their protein-rich whites and nutrient-dense yolks.
Tomatoes are edible berries of the tomato plant, used in salads, sauces, and many cuisines around the world.
Almonds are the edible seeds of the almond tree, commonly eaten raw, roasted, or as a component of various dishes.
Lettuce is a leafy green vegetable often used in salads and sandwiches.
Beef steak is a slice of meat cut from the flesh of a cow, typically cooked by grilling or pan-frying.
Milk is a nutrient-rich liquid food produced by mammals, commonly consumed as a beverage or used in cooking.
Quinoa is a seed that is cooked and eaten like a grain, known for being high in protein and gluten-free.
Yogurt is a fermented dairy product made by adding bacteria to milk, known for its creamy texture and probiotic content.
Spinach is a leafy green vegetable that is rich in iron and vitamins, often used in salads or cooked dishes.
Cheese is a dairy product made from curdled milk, available in many varieties and used in cooking or eaten on its own.
Oats are whole grains that are commonly used to make oatmeal or baked into various goods, providing a healthy source of fiber.
